Abstract

Within the framework of Topological Dynamic Membrane Universe (TDMU 2.32), this paper constructs a geometric model of black-hole-grade topological stars. The physical entity is a superfluid vortex core in a state of global phase locking; released energy is transformed into vortex twist energy via a three-step mechanism, contributing an effective mass, while a triple geometric confinement tames the centrifugal storm. The optical appearance is governed by first-order and second-order effects of the shared-link density gradient, producing a four-layer structure, in which the photon capture shell possesses a finite thickness, constituting a testable divide from the zero-thickness photon sphere of general relativity. The same set of geometric parameters provides a unified description of the existence of the lower mass limit, the mass gap, and the upper mass limit — corresponding respectively to the critical closure of the superfluid shell, the unstable region of the semi-closed phase transition, and the collapse point of the vortex-network phase locking. Sgr A* and M87 are used as case studies to demonstrate the observational differences of the same engine operating under low-accretion and high-accretion conditions. The rapid formation of high-redshift supermassive black holes is achieved through three-channel parallel growth, without the need for a seed black hole hypothesis. The model provides five testable predictions with clear discriminative power.

1. Introduction

1.1 Unclosed Problems of the Standard Model

The black hole model within the framework of general relativity harbors deep theoretical tensions.

Singularity problem. General relativity predicts that spacetime curvature diverges at the center of a black hole, signaling the failure of the theory under extreme conditions. A physically unacceptable infinity is packaged as a mathematical singularity.

Information paradox. Hawking radiation is derived to have a purely thermal spectrum, causing the initial quantum information to be lost during the evaporation process, directly conflicting with the unitarity of quantum mechanics. This has remained unresolved for half a century.

Multi-mechanism patchwork. Gravity invokes general relativity; accretion disk radiation invokes magnetohydrodynamics; jets invoke the Blandford–Znajek mechanism; Hawking radiation invokes quantum field theory in curved spacetime. Four observational phenomena rely on four independent mechanisms, lacking a unified underlying language.

Seed black hole dilemma. Quasars with masses exceeding one billion solar masses have been observed at high redshifts, when the Universe was only about 700 million years old. The time required to grow from a stellar-mass seed via continuous accretion at the Eddington limit far exceeds this limit. The abundance of light seeds (Population III stellar remnants, about one hundred solar masses) is questionable, and the formation conditions for heavy seeds (direct collapse of primordial gas clouds, about one hundred thousand solar masses) are stringent; both lack direct observational evidence.

No unified explanation for the triple mass constraints. The lower limit invokes the neutron-star equation of state limit; the mass gap invokes supernova explosion asymmetry; the upper limit invokes the Eddington accretion rate limit. Three independent assumptions, no unified language.

