*6. Case Studies: Sgr A and M87**

6.1 Sgr A*: Low-Accretion State

Mass approximately four million solar masses; distance approximately eight kiloparsecs; currently in a long-term low-accretion state.

External matter supply is extremely low; the Galactic Center environment is relatively sparse. Path Two is only triggered sporadically; a small amount of matter falls accidentally within the fission surface, triggering local forced chain reconnection, manifesting as isolated X-ray and infrared flares. The flare frequency and intensity reflect the random fluctuations of the external matter supply. Path One operates continuously, maintaining the basic operation of the core vortex system. The photon ring is nearly invisible due to insufficient fuel.

The spin parameter is about 0.5 to 0.9, not inherited from a progenitor star. During accretion, the internal vortex tubes are gradually aligned into an ordered configuration by the rotation direction of the involutional flow—the angular momentum carried by the accreted matter combs the orientation of the vortex tubes through the shared-link network. The spin value reflects the cumulative combing effect of all matter accreted over the history of the Milky Way.

No significant jet. The degree of equatorial pile-up is insufficient to activate the polar extrusion channel. The triple geometric confinement ensures that the core remains stable even in the absence of external matter support; the mass is frozen in the form of vortex twist energy and does not rely on external pressure for maintenance.

6.2 M87*: High-Accretion State

Mass approximately 6.5 billion solar masses; distance approximately 16.8 megaparsecs; in a high-accretion active state.

External matter supply is abundant; the environment at the center of the M87 galaxy is dense. Path Two is triggered continuously, and the bright ring layer is persistently luminous. The photon ring has been clearly imaged by the EHT.

The jet extends from the core to thousands of light-years and is extremely collimated. The geometric origin of the jet is a natural byproduct of the triple confinement mechanism. The centrifugal tendency of the vortices is strongest in the equatorial plane and is locked by the triple confinement, causing equatorial flattening and stress pile-up. Along the polar axis, the centrifugal tendency is zero and the involutional flow shear force is minimal. The excessively piled-up vortex stress is released along the polar axis—the jet is the exhaust port of the geometric engine, requiring no magnetic-field-driven hypothesis. The jet power is directly related to the energy injection rate of Path Two.

6.3 Essence of the Difference

The internal structures of the two objects are identical. Both cores are phase-locked superfluid vortex systems, both are subject to the triple geometric confinement, and both rely on two energy channels to maintain operation. The difference arises solely from the influence of the external matter supply rate on the trigger frequency of Path Two.

If the matter supply to the Galactic Center were to increase suddenly, Sgr A* would undergo a transition: activation of the quiet region, surge in bright ring layer brightness, outward migration of the fission surface, and emergence of a jet from nothing. This transition is directly observable. Conversely, if the accretion supply to M87* were cut off, it would gradually dim and eventually present a dormant state similar to Sgr A*.

