9. Testable Predictions

The following five predictions are all clearly distinguishable from the general relativistic model.

Prediction 1: Finite Thickness of the Photon Ring.

The photon capture shell thickness is greater than zero. The quantitative relationships among the thickness, mass, and spin have not yet been derived, but systematic trends are qualitatively expected. Measurements can be performed on multiple supermassive objects using the Event Horizon Telescope and next-generation space VLBI. General relativity predicts a zero-thickness photon sphere; TDMU predicts a finite-thickness shell.

Prediction 2: Stable Black Holes with Extreme Spin.

The triple geometric confinement provides structural stability beyond the limit set by accretion disk radiation reaction, allowing the existence of stable objects with spin parameters approaching unity. Gravitational-wave detectors (LIGO/Virgo/KAGRA) can search for candidates with spin parameters exceeding 0.998. The general relativistic Thorne limit is an accretion limit, not a structural limit of the black hole.

Prediction 3: Offset Between Bright Ring Peak and Matter Truncation.

The photon ring brightness peak is located at the tangential capture surface, while the matter disruption boundary is located at the fission surface; the two do not coincide. High-resolution joint X-ray and radio observations can resolve the spatial offset. In general relativity, the two coincide near the innermost stable circular orbit.

Prediction 4: Discrete Spectrum of Post-Merger Echoes.

After two topological stars merge, the process of re-establishing phase locking in the new core produces gravitational-wave aftershocks. The aftershock frequencies form a discrete sequence, corresponding to different orders of vortex reorganization modes. The frequencies are determined by the ratio of the core filling factor to the suture line stress. The general relativistic no-hair theorem predicts no subsequent signal after the merger. The discrete sequence structure is a unique imprint that distinguishes TDMU from other alternative theories.

Prediction 5: Matter-Dependence of the Truncation Radius.

The fission surface is determined by the compressive binding energy of the accreted matter. Matter containing complex nuclides has higher compressive binding energy, and the disruption boundary lies further out. The inner edge positions of accretion disks with different metallicities should exhibit systematic differences. In general relativity, the accretion disk truncation has no direct connection with the matter composition.

10. Theoretical Gaps

The following issues have not yet been quantitatively derived.

First, the precise critical mass for the closure of the surface superfluid shell requires the statistical mechanics of the surface link network; currently, only a qualitative criterion is available.

Second, the scaling factor for the ratio of vortex energy to total mass requires the statistical mechanics of the vortex network and has not yet been derived.

Third, the functional relationship between the critical vortex density and the core filling factor has not yet been established, and the specific numerical value of the upper mass limit cannot be calculated at present.

Fourth, the precise mapping from the characteristic optical radii to the effective mass, spin, and filling factor has not yet been completed.

Fifth, the conversion relationships from the theoretical geometric units (reconnection steps, link density, etc.) to measurable physical units have not yet been determined.

Sixth, the initial mass spectrum of topological stars in the early Universe has not yet been quantitatively derived from the first principles of TDMU cosmology.

11. Conclusion

This paper constructs a complete geometric model of black-hole-grade topological stars within the TDMU 2.32 framework.

Physical entity. A black hole is a superfluid vortex geometric engine. The interior is globally phase-locked; released energy is transformed into vortex twist energy via a three-step phonon-to-vortex mechanism, contributing an effective mass. The triple geometric confinement tames the centrifugal storm; equatorial flattening and polar jets are its macroscopic manifestations.

Optical appearance. The first-order and second-order effects of the shared-link density gradient produce a four-layer structure. The photon capture shell has a finite thickness, forming a direct divide from the zero-thickness photon sphere of general relativity.

Triple mass constraints. The existence of the lower limit, the gap, and the upper limit is unifiedly explained by the surface coherence, the core filling factor, and the vortex geometric capacity, without invoking equations of state, explosion asymmetry, or radiation pressure limits.

Sgr A* and M87 are manifestations of the same engine under different external matter supply rates. The difference lies in the external environment, not in the internal structure.

High-redshift supermassive black holes form naturally through three-channel parallel growth.

The five testable predictions are: finite thickness of the photon ring, extreme spin stability, offset between the bright ring and matter truncation, discrete spectrum of merger echoes, and matter-dependence of the truncation radius.

The “blackness” of a black hole is an optical illusion caused by light being gradient-locked under extreme geometric conditions. Its interior is a ceaseless vortex storm, tamed by a triple geometric shackle. TDMU restores the black hole to its full status as a physical entity possessing a rich internal structure and observable geometric hair.

